8 An Act relating to vital records; amending 63 O.S.
2021, Section 1-321, as last amended by Section 10,
9 Chapter 58, O.S.L. 2025 (63 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
1-321), which relates to amendment of certificate or
10 records; prohibiting amendments to biological sex on
certificate of birth; and providing an effective
11 date.
12
13 AUTHOR: Add the following Senate Coauthor: Burns
14 AMENDMENT NO. 1. Page 1, strike the title, enacting clause and
entire bill and insert
15
16 “An Act relating to vital records; providing findings
and declarations; amending 63 O.S. 2021, Sections 1-
17 311, as last amended by Section 2, Chapter 58, O.S.L.
2025, 1-313, as amended by Section 2, Chapter 87,
18 O.S.L. 2022, 1-316, as amended by Section 3, Chapter
87, O.S.L. 2022, and 1-321, as last amended by
19 Section 10, Chapter 58, O.S.L. 2025 (63 O.S. Supp.
2025, Sections 1-311, 1-313, 1-316, and 1-321), which
20 relate to certificates of birth; updating statutory
language; requiring certificates of birth to contain
21 accurate biological sex designations; clarifying
certain requirement and prohibitions; updating
22 statutory reference; providing for noncodification;
and declaring an emergency.
23
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 1

1 BE I T ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
2 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
3 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
4 The Legislature finds and declares that it is enacting the
5 following statutory changes “to clarify existing law, as opposed to
6 altering its substance” per Purcell v. Santa Fe Minerals, Inc., 1998
7 OK 45, 961 P.2d 188. The Legislature further finds and declares
8 that these clarifications are important to protect, among other
9 things, the integrity and accuracy of vital statistics records. In
10 particular, the Legislature finds that private parties have been
11 wrongly asserting in court that the Legislature’s previous law
12 clarifying Oklahoma birth certificate statutes, Senate Bill No. 1100
13 of the 2nd Session of the 58th Oklahoma Legislature, constituted an
14 acquiescence to the unauthorized practice of changing the biological
15 sex designation on birth certificates to represent a person’s gender
16 identity. The Legislature finds and declares that Senate Bill No.
17 1100 of the 2nd Session of the 58th Oklahoma Legislature did nothing
18 of the sort; rather, it was intended to clarify, in response to
19 revelations about an unsanctioned settlement over a nonbinary
20 designation, that Oklahoma birth certificates are supposed to
21 contain a biological sex designation only, and that this designation
22 should not be altered to display gender identity, a nonbinary
23 designation, or anything other than a male or female designation.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 2

1 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 1-311, as
2 last amended by Section 2, Chapter 58, O.S.L. 2025 (63 O.S. Supp.
3 2025, Section 1-311), is amended to read as follows:
4 Section 1-311. A. A certificate of birth for each live birth
5 which occurs in this state shall be filed with the State
6 Commissioner of Health within seven (7) days after the birth.
7 B. When a birth occurs in an institution, the person in charge
8 of the institution or a designated representative shall obtain the
9 personal data, prepare the certificate and secure the signatures
10 required by the certificate. The physician in attendance shall
11 certify to the facts of birth and provide the medical information
12 required by the certificate within five (5) days after the birth.
13 C. When a birth occurs outside an institution, the certificate
14 shall be prepared and filed by one of the following in the indicated
15 order of priority:
16 1. The physician in attendance at or immediately after the
17 birth;
18 2. Any other person in attendance at or immediately after the
19 birth; or
20 3. The father, the mother or, in the absence or inability of
21 the father or mother, the person in charge of the premises where the
22 birth occurred and present at the birth.
23 D. 1. If the mother was married at the time of birth, or
24 married at any time during the three hundred (300) calendar days
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 3

1 befo re the birth, the name of the husband shall be entered on the
2 certificate as the father of the child unless paternity has been
3 determined otherwise by a court of competent jurisdiction or a
4 husband’s denial of paternity form has been filed along with an
5 affidavit acknowledging paternity, in which case the name of the
6 father as determined by the court or affidavit acknowledging
7 paternity shall be entered. If there is a refusal to identify
8 paternity on the birth certificate, the State Department of Health
9 is authorized to register a birth certificate as such.
10 2. If the mother was not married at the time of birth, nor
11 married at any time during the three hundred (300) calendar days
12 before the birth, the name of the father shall be entered on the
13 certificate of birth only if:
14 a. a determination of paternity has been made by an
15 administrative action through the Department of Human
16 Services or a court of competent jurisdiction, in
17 which case the name of the father shall be entered, or
18 b. the mother and father have agreed as to the biological
19 paternity of the child and signed an acknowledgment of
20 paternity pursuant to Section 1-311.3 of this title,
21 or substantially similar affidavit from another state
22 and filed it with the State Commissioner of Health.
23 This shall give the unmarried mother and biological father equal
24 rights and obligations to the child. A child whose parentage has
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 4

1 been determined as set forth shall be treated as a child of parents
2 who were married at the time of the birth.
3 E. Either of the parents of the child shall sign the
4 certificate of live birth worksheet to attest to the accuracy of the
5 personal data entered thereon, in time to permit its filing within
6 the seven (7) days prescribed in this section.
7 F. If the live birth results from a process in which the
8 delivering mother was carrying the child of another woman by way of
9 a prearranged legal contract, the original birth certificate shall
10 be filed with the personal information of the woman who delivered
11 the child. A new birth certificate will be placed on file once the
12 Department receives both a court order and a completed form
13 prescribed by the Department which identifies the various parties
14 and documents the personal information of the intended parents
15 necessary to complete the new birth certificate.
16 G. Beginning on April 25, 2022, the biological sex designation
17 on a Every certificate of birth issued under this section shall be
18 contain an accurate biological sex designation of either male or
19 female and, as identified at the time of birth. The biological sex
20 designation shall not be display gender identity, a nonbinary
21 designation, or any symbol representing a nonbinary designation
22 including, but not limited to, the letter “X”.
23
