1 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 1-313, as
2 amended by Section 2, Chapter 87, O.S.L. 2022 (63 O.S. Supp. 2025,
3 Section 1-313), is amended to read as follows:
4 Section 1-313. A. When the birth of a person born in this
5 state has not been registered, a certificate may be filed in
6 accordance with regulations of the State Commissioner of Health.
7 Such certificate shall be registered subject to such evidentiary
8 requirements as the Commissioner shall by regulation prescribe, to
9 substantiate the alleged facts of birth.
10 B. Certificates of birth registered one (1) year or more after
11 the date of occurrence shall be marked “delayed” and show on their
12 face the date of the delayed registration.
13 C. A summary statement of the evidence submitted in support of
14 the delayed registration shall be endorsed on the certificate.
15 D. When an applicant does not submit the minimum documentation
16 required in the regulations for delayed registration, or when the
17 State Commissioner of Health finds reason to question the validity
18 or adequacy of the documentary evidence, the Commissioner shall not
19 register the delayed certificate and shall advise the applicant of
20 the reasons for his or her action.
21 E. Beginning on the effective date of this act, the biological
22 sex designation on a Every certificate of birth issued under this
23 section shall be contain an accurate biological sex designation of
24 either male or female and, as identified at the time of birth. The
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 6

1 biol ogical sex designation shall not be display gender identity, a
2 nonbinary designation, or any symbol representing a nonbinary
3 designation including, but not limited to, the letter “X”.
4 SECTION 4. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 1-316, as
5 amended by Section 3, Chapter 87, O.S.L. 2022 (63 O.S. Supp. 2025,
6 Section 1-316), is amended to read as follows:
7 Section 1-316. A. The State Commissioner of Health shall
8 establish a new certificate of birth for a person born in this
9 state, when the Commissioner receives the following:
10 1. An adoption certificate as provided in the Oklahoma Adoption
11 Code, or a certified copy of the decree of adoption together with
12 the information necessary to identify the original certificate of
13 birth and to establish a new certificate of birth; except that a new
14 certificate of birth shall not be established if so requested by the
15 court decreeing the adoption, the adoptive parents or the adopted
16 person; and
17 2. A request that a new certificate be established and such
18 evidence as required by regulation proving that such person has been
19 legitimated, or that a court of competent jurisdiction has
20 determined the paternity of such a person.
21 B. When a new certificate of birth is established, the actual
22 place and date of birth shall be shown. It shall be substituted for
23 the original certificate of birth:
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 7

1 1. Thereafter, the original certificate and the evidence of
2 adoption, paternity or legitimation shall not be amended, nor shall
3 it be subject to inspection except upon order of a court of
4 competent jurisdiction or as otherwise specifically provided by law;
5 and
6 2. Upon receipt of notice of annulment of adoption, the
7 original certificate of birth shall be restored to its place in the
8 files and the new certificate and evidence shall not be subject to
9 inspection except upon order of a court of competent jurisdiction.
10 The original certificate shall be restored and may be amended in
11 accordance with Section 1-321 of this title.
12 C. Beginning on the effective date of this act, the biological
13 sex designation on a Every new certificate of birth issued under
14 this section shall be contain an accurate biological sex designation
15 of either male or female and, as identified at the time of birth.
16 The biological sex designation shall not be display gender identity,
17 a nonbinary designation, or any symbol representing a nonbinary
18 designation including, but not limited to, the letter “X”.
19 SECTION 5. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 1-321, as
20 last amended by Section 10, Chapter 58, O.S.L. 2025 (63 O.S. Supp.
21 2025, Section 1-321), is amended to read as follows:
22 Section 1-321. A. A certificate or record registered under
23 this article may be amended only in accordance with this article and
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 8

1 regu lations thereunder adopted by the State Commissioner of Health
2 to protect the integrity and accuracy of vital statistics records.
3 B. A certificate that is amended under this section shall be
4 marked “amended”, except as provided in subsection D E of this
5 section. The date of amendment and a summary description of the
6 evidence submitted in support of the amendment shall be endorsed on
7 or made a part of the record.
8 The Commissioner shall prescribe by regulation the conditions under
9 which additions or minor corrections shall be made to birth
10 certificates within one (1) year after the date of birth without the
11 certificate being considered as amended. Certificates shall be
12 marked as “amended” for minor corrections made one (1) year after
13 the date of birth.
14 C. Upon receipt of a certified copy of a court order, from a
15 court of competent jurisdiction, changing the name of a person born
16 in this state and upon request of such person or his or her parent,
17 guardian or legal representative, the State Commissioner of Health
18 shall amend the certificate of birth to reflect the new name.
19 D. When a child is born out of wedlock, the Commissioner shall
20 amend a certificate of birth to show paternity, if paternity is not
21 currently shown on the birth certificate, in the following
22 situations:
23 1. Upon request and receipt of a sworn acknowledgment of
24 paternity of a child born out of wedlock signed by both parents;
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 9

1 2. Upon receipt of a certified copy of a court order
2 adjudicating paternity; or
3 3. Upon receipt of an electronic record from the Department of
4 Human Services indicating that an acknowledgment of paternity has
5 been signed by both parents or a court order adjudicating paternity.
6 E. For a child born out of wedlock, the Commissioner shall also
7 change the surname of the child on the certificate:
8 1. To the specified surname upon receipt of acknowledgment of
9 paternity signed by both parents, upon receipt of a certified copy
10 of a court order directing such name be changed or upon receipt of
11 an electronic record from the Department of Human Services
12 indicating that an acknowledgment of paternity has been signed by
13 both parents or a court order directs such name change. Such
14 certificate amended pursuant to this subsection shall not be marked
15 “amended”; or
16 2. To the surname of the mother on the birth certificate in the
17 event the acknowledgment of paternity is rescinded.
18 F. The Commissioner shall have the power and duty to promulgate
19 rules for situations in which the Department receives false
20 information regarding the identity of a parent.
21 G. If within one (1) year of the initial issuance of a
22 certificate of death, a funeral director, or a person acting as
23 such, requests a correction to any portion of the death record
24 except the information relating to the medical certification
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1225 Page 10

1 port ion, due to a scrivener’s error, misspelling or other correction
2 of information, the State Commissioner of Health, through the State
3 Registrar of Vital Statistics, shall amend the record, provided the
4 request is made in writing or through an electronic system and is
5 accompanied by documentation disclosing the correct information or
6 by a sworn statement of the funeral director. The funeral director,
7 or person acting as such, shall be responsible for any and all
8 amendment fees that may be imposed by the State Commissioner of
9 Health for the correction. Up to ten certified copies containing
10 the erroneous original information may be exchanged for certified
11 copies containing the corrected information at no additional cost.
12 H. Beginning April 26, 2022, the biological sex designation on
13 a Every certificate of birth amended under this section shall be
14 contain an accurate biological sex designation of either male or
15 female and shall not be, as identified at the time of birth. The
16 biological sex designation shall not be amended to display gender
17 identity, a nonbinary designation, or any symbol representing a
18 nonbinary designation including but not limited to the letter “X”.
19 SECTION 6. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
20 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
21 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
22 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.”
